english:
  title: Prayer to the Great One
  author: Lee Seung-so
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Silent and scentless, you turn the mechanisms of creation in stillness.
    Like one scorched by fire, burned by flame, I have long suffered
    under the tyranny of drought's cruel hand.
    Now I pour out my whole heart in earnest prayer,
    lifting my face to beg for your hidden grace.

    I reflect with shame: bearing meager gifts,
    I have inherited a burden vast and heavy.
    Though I seek wisdom in humble study,
    I remain blind to how heaven and earth respond to one another.
    Though I labor to refine my conduct,
    I cannot grasp the sage's way of governing the realm.
    In serving the spirits and ruling the people,
    my reverence falls short of true sincerity.
    In issuing commands and edicts,
    how can I claim they all accord with the times?

    Moreover, so insignificant in this single body,
    I dwell deep within the nine-fold palace walls.
    My wisdom cannot reach all that concerns the ten thousand things,
    my sight and hearing cannot span every direction.
    My will does not rise to touch the heavens above—
    so the prisons overflow with the wrongly condemned.
    My virtue does not descend to those below—
    so the fields echo with sighs of sorrow.

    Hostile winds have gathered, evil omens multiply:
    winter brings no snow, summer brings no rain.
    Through three seasons the sun blazes alone.
    Barley cannot head, rice cannot sprout.
    With all growing things, they wither together.
    Having lost the spring planting,
    how can we hope for autumn's harvest?

    In this stillness, I understand:
    the fault lies with me, this one person.
    Yet all are drowning together—
    what crime have my innocent people committed?

    So I approach this humble altar,
    humbly presenting these rites of prayer.
    If my faint sincerity can move your heart,
    mayhap your great blessings will swiftly descend.

    I reverently pray:
    Let the two vital breaths harmonize,
    let all the spirits fulfill their roles.
    Let clouds gather and rain pour down,
    that the hundred grains may ripen full.
    Let the fields be combed as fine as silk,
    let the granaries rise high as walls,
    filled to overflow with abundance.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This is a state ritual prayer (醮禮) composed during a time of severe drought, reflecting both Daoist cosmological concepts and Confucian notions of the ruler's moral responsibility for natural harmony.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'nine-fold palace' (九重) refers to the emperor's palace, emphasizing the isolation of the ruler from direct knowledge of the people's suffering.
  - key: ''
    value: The prayer employs the traditional Confucian idea that natural disasters are celestial responses to moral failing—here, the ruler takes full responsibility for the drought as a consequence of his inadequacy.
